column7: Sections show a dermal cellular proliferation of pleomorphic and spindle cells with frequent mitoses, with extension into the subcutis. Comment: Tumors with features similar to atypical fibroxanthoma but with additional significant subcutaneous extension are classified as pleomorphic dermal scarcoma due to their finite but real risk of aggressive behavior, including risk of local recurrence and occasionally metastasis. Reference: Miller K. et al. Pleomorphic Dermal Sarcoma: Adverse Histologic Features Predict Aggressive Behavior and Allow for Distinction From Atypical Fibroxanthoma. Am J Surg Pathol 2012, Sep;36(9):1317-26

Many authors consider atypical fibroxanthoma to represent a superficial variant of pleomorphic dermal sarcoma (formerly known as malignant fibrous histiocytoma), in which the better prognosis is due to the superficial location. If this lesion extends deeply into the subcutis, the prognosis may not be as good as would be expected for an atypical fibroxanthoma. Reference: Miller K. et al. Pleomorphic Dermal Sarcoma: Adverse Histologic Features Predict Aggressive Behavior and Allow for Distinction From Atypical Fibroxanthoma. Am J Surg Pathol 2012, Sep;36(9):1317-26

If this is a small lesion confined to the dermis, the morphologic and immunophenotypic findings would be consistent with an atypical fibroxanthoma. However, poorly differentiated/sarcomatoid squamous cell carcinoma or a pleomorphic dermal sarcoma (formerly known as MFH") cannot be excluded on this biopsy. Final diagnosis will rest upon examination of the completely excised specimen."

column6: The differential diagnosis for lymphocyte-mediated scarring alopecia with interface injury includes frontal fibrosing alopecia/lichen planopilaris and lupus erythematosus. While lupus cannot be entirely excluded, the lack of interfollicular interface injury or an increase in dermal mucin, as well as the lack of deep perifollicular inflammation or a significant perivascular component to the inflammation, support the diagnosis of frontal fibrosing alopecia over lupus, particularly in this clinical context.
column7: At the level of the isthmus, there is disruption of the normal follicular unit architecture,with fibrosis and decreased to absent sebaceous glands. At this level of sectioning, many of the remaining hair follicles demonstrate concentric perifollicular fibrosis, and interface injury with a lichenoid lymphocytic infiltrate. No interfollicular interface injury is seen at the dermoepidermal junction, and there is no apparent increase in dermal mucin. A periodic acid-Schiff stain was utilized in the diagnostic evaluation (and is negative for fungus).
The specimen consists of predominantly anagen hairs, several of which have ruffled cuticles and 'hockey stick' appearance. All of the hairs lack root sheaths.

column6: The differential diagnosis for lymphocyte-mediated scarring alopecia with interface injury includes lichen planopilaris and lupus erythematosus. While lichen planopilaris cannot be entirely excluded, the presence of interfollicular interface injury and increased dermal mucin, as well as the depth of perifollicular inflammation and perivascular extension of the inflammation, support the diagnosis of lupus over lichen planopilaris in this biopsy.
column7: At the level of the isthmus, there is disruption of the normal follicular unit architecture,with fibrosis and decreased to absent sebaceous glands. At this level of sectioning, many of the remaining hair follicles demonstrate concentric perifollicular fibrosis, and interface injury with a lichenoid lymphocytic infiltrate, which extends to the suprabulbar portion of the follicles. The epidermis demonstrates interface injury as well, and acanthosis with hyperkeratosis. There is also an increase in dermal mucin. A periodic acid-Schiff stain was utilized in the diagnostic evaluation (and is negative for fungus).

column6: The findings in this biopsy are subtle. The differential diagnosis includes an early stage of androgenetic alopecia, resolving telogen effluvium, or diffuse alopecia areata. Due to the sampling variability inherent in scalp biopsies for alopecia, additional sampling from the advancing edge could be considered, if clinically indicated.
column7: There is a slight decrease in follicle density, with no evidence of scarring or significant inflammation. The terminal to vellus hair ratio and percentage of catagen/telogen hair follicles are essentially within normal limits.  A periodic acid-Schiff stain was utilized in the diagnostic evaluation (and is negative for fungus).

column6: This is a challenging case as spitzoid lesions are notoriously difficult to categorize and predict the clinical behavior of, particularly in adults. Although there are several overlapping features with an atypical Spitz tumor, and some would consider an interpretation of atypical Spitz tumor/melanocytic tumor of uncertain malignant potential, this lesion has a number of concerning features. The lesion is asymmetric, deep, fails to mature, demonstrates marked pleomorphism, and contains dermal mitoses. Given these features, particularly in a patient this age, we all favor interpretation and treatment as a spitzoid melanoma.
